setenumi{2}]
\latex default 
 
\series bold 
[2 marks]
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

The 
\series bold 
\shape italic 
\color red
Extreme Value Theorem
\series default 
\shape default 
\color default
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite[Section 4.2, Theorem 3]{Steward}

\end_inset 

)guarantess the existence of absolute maximums and minimums for continuous
 functions on closed intervals.
\layout Enumerate

The suggested steps to find the absolute maximum and the absolute minimum
 of a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 over a closed interval 
\begin_inset Formula \( [a,b] \)
\end_inset 

 are outlined as the 
\series bold 
\shape italic 
\color red
Closed Interval Method
\series default 
\shape default 
\color default
 (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite[Section 4.2, p. 275]{Steward}

\end_inset 

).
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

Find the values of 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 at the critical numbers of 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 in 
\begin_inset Formula \( (a,b) \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Enumerate

Find the values of 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 at the endpoints of the interval.
\layout Enumerate

The largest of the values from Steps 1 and 2 is the absolute maximum value;
 the smallest of these values is the absolute minimum value.
\end_deeper 
\end_deeper 
\layout Enumerate


\latex latex 
[
\backslash 
setenumi{4}]
\latex default 
 
\series bold 
[2 marks]
\series default 
 We will be using definition 2 from Stewart (
\begin_inset LatexCommand \cite[Section 4.2, Definition 2]{Steward}

\end_inset 

).
 Specifically, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 has a local maximum at 
\begin_inset Formula \( c \)
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula \( f(c)\geq f(x) \)
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula \( x \)
\end_inset 

 is a neighbourhood of 
\begin_inset Formula \( c \)
\end_inset 

.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 has a local minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula \( c \)
\end_inset 

 if 
\begin_inset Formula \( f(c)\leq f(x) \)
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula \( x \)
\end_inset 

 is a neighbourhood of 
\begin_inset Formula \( c \)
\end_inset 

.
