\layout Enumerate


\latex latex 
[
\backslash 
setenumi{28}]
\latex default 
 
\series bold 
[2 marks]
\series default 
 A critical number is a number 
\begin_inset Formula \( c \)
\end_inset 

 where either 
\begin_inset Formula \( f'(c)=0 \)
\end_inset 

 or else 
\begin_inset Formula \( f'(c)\, \nexists  \)
\end_inset 

.
 Using the quotient rule, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
f'(x) & = & \frac{x^{2}+x+1-(x+1)(2x+1)}{(x^{2}+x+1)^{2}}\\
 & = & \frac{-x^{2}-2x}{(x^{2}+x+1)^{2}}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset 

Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula \( f'(c)\, \nexists  \)
\end_inset 

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula \( x^{2}+x+1=0 \)
\end_inset 

 (and actually, that's true for 
\begin_inset Formula \( f \)
\end_inset 

 itself!), but using the quadratic rule we notice that this equation has
 no real solution since the discriminant is negative (
\begin_inset Formula \( b^{2}-4ac=1-4=-3) \)
\end_inset 

.
 We conclude that the derivative always exists.
 However, the derivative is zero whenever 
\begin_inset Formula \( -x^{2}-2x=0\Rightarrow x\in \{0,-2\} \)
\end_inset 

.
 Therefore, we have found the two critical points: 
\begin_inset Formula \( \{0,-2\} \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Enumerate


\latex latex 
[
\backslash 
setenumi{38}]
\latex default 
 
\series bold 
[3 marks]
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

The critical points of 
\begin_inset Formula \( \sqrt{9-x^{2}} \)
\end_inset 

 are found by taking the derivative which is 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\frac{-x}{\sqrt{9-x^{2}}}.\]

\end_inset 

The derivative doesn't exist whenever 
\begin_inset Formula \( 9-x^{2}\leq 0 \)
\end_inset 

 which happens whenever 
\begin_inset Formula \( x\notin (-3,3) \)
\end_inset 

 but on the proposed interval (
\begin_inset Formula \( [-1,2] \)
\end_inset 

), it isn't an issue.
 However, the derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula \( 0 \)
\end_inset 

 when 
\begin_inset Formula \( x=0 \)
\end_inset 

 and thus we have one (and only one) critical point (
\begin_inset Formula \( x=0 \)
\end_inset 

).
 The value of the function at the critical point is
\color blue
 
\begin_inset Formula \( f(0)=3 \)
\end_inset 


\color default
.
\layout Enumerate

We have to evaluate the function at the boundary of the closed interval.
 We readily obtain 
\color blue

\begin_inset Formula \( f(-1)=2\sqrt{2} \)
\end_inset 


\color default
 and 
\color blue

\begin_inset Formula \( f(2)=\sqrt{5} \)
\end_inset 


\color default
.
\layout Enumerate

The absolute maximum is 
\begin_inset Formula \( 3 \)
\end_inset 

 and it is reached at 
\begin_inset Formula \( x=0 \)
\end_inset 

.
 The absolute minimum is 
\begin_inset Formula \( \sqrt{5} \)
\end_inset 

 and it is reached at 
\begin_inset Formula \( x=2 \)
\end_inset 

.
 The third critical point (
\begin_inset Formula \( x=-1) \)
\end_inset 

 is a local minimum.
\begin_float fig 
\end_deeper 
\layout Standard


