\end_inset 


\layout Caption


\begin_inset Formula \( \sqrt{9-x^{2}} \)
\end_inset 

 
\end_float 
\layout Enumerate


\latex latex 
[
\backslash 
setenumi{42}]
\latex default 
 
\series bold 
[3 marks]
\begin_deeper 
\layout Enumerate

The critical points of 
\begin_inset Formula \( f(x)=x-2\cos x \)
\end_inset 

 are found through the derivative which is
\begin_inset Formula \[
f'(x)=1+2\sin x.\]

\end_inset 

Clearly, the derivative always exist.
 It is zero whenever 
\begin_inset Formula \( \sin x=\frac{-1}{2} \)
\end_inset 

 or when 
\begin_inset Formula \( x=-\frac{\pi }{6}+2\pi k \)
\end_inset 

 where 
\begin_inset Formula \( k \)
\end_inset 

 is an integer.
 There is only one such critical point in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula \( [-\pi ,\pi ] \)
\end_inset 

 and that's 
\begin_inset Formula \( -\frac{\pi }{6} \)
\end_inset 

.
 We evaluate the function at this critical point 
\color red

\begin_inset Formula \( f\left( -\frac{\pi }{6}\right) =-\frac{\pi }{6}-\sqrt{3}\cong -2.26 \)
\end_inset 

.
\layout Enumerate

We evaluate the function at the boundary of the interval: 
\color red

\begin_inset Formula \( f(-\pi )=-\pi +2\cong -1.1 \)
\end_inset 


\color default
 and 
\color red

\begin_inset Formula \( f(\pi )=\pi +2\cong 5.1 \)
\end_inset 

 
\color default
.
\layout Enumerate

We see that the absolute maximum is reached at 
\begin_inset Formula \( f(\pi )=\pi +2 \)
\end_inset 

 and the absolute minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula \( f\left( -\frac{\pi }{6}\right) =-\frac{\pi }{6}-\sqrt{3} \)
\end_inset 

.
 
\begin_inset Formula \( f(-\pi )=-\pi +2 \)
\end_inset 

 is a local minimum.
\begin_float fig 
\end_deeper 
\layout Standard


\latex latex 
[h]
\layout Standard
\align center 

\begin_inset Figure size 239 168
file 4_2_42
height 3 20
