flags 9

\end_inset 


\layout Caption


\begin_inset Formula \( x-2\cos x \)
\end_inset 


\end_float 
\layout Enumerate


\latex latex 
[
\backslash 
setenumi{52}]
\latex default 
 
\series bold 
[2 marks]
\series default 
 The independent variable is 
\begin_inset Formula \( \theta  \)
\end_inset 

.
 We can take the derivative either using the chain rule or else, using the
 quotient rule.
 We get 
\begin_inset Formula \[
F'(\theta )=\frac{\mu W\left( \sin \theta -\mu \cos \theta \right) }{\left( \mu \sin \theta +\cos \theta \right) ^{2}}.\]

\end_inset 

Setting 
\begin_inset Formula \( F'(\theta )=0 \)
\end_inset 

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula \( \sin \theta -\mu \cos \theta =0 \)
\end_inset 

 or 
\begin_inset Formula \( \mu =\tan \theta  \)
\end_inset 

.
 To verify that it is a minimum, we take the second derivative (using the
 quotient rule)
\begin_inset Formula \[
F''(\theta )=\frac{\mu W\left( 3\left( \sin \theta -\mu \cos \theta \right) ^{2}\left( \mu \sin \theta +\cos \theta \right) +\left( \mu \sin \theta +\cos \theta \right) ^{3}\right) }{\left( \mu \sin \theta +\cos \theta \right) ^{3}}.\]

\end_inset 

Assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula \( \sin \theta -\mu \cos \theta =0 \)
\end_inset 

,
\begin_inset Formula \[
F''(\theta )=\frac{\mu W\left( \left( \mu \sin \theta +\cos \theta \right) ^{3}\right) }{\left( \mu \sin \theta +\cos \theta \right) ^{3}}=\mu .\]

\end_inset 

Since 
\begin_inset Formula \( \tan \theta =\mu  \)
\end_inset 

 is positive (recall that 
\begin_inset Formula \( 0\leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi }{2} \)
\end_inset 

) and so is the weight 
\begin_inset Formula \( W \)
\end_inset 

, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula \( F''(\theta )>0 \)
\end_inset 

 and so, 
\begin_inset Formula \( \mu =\tan \theta  \)
\end_inset 

 is a local minimum.
\begin_float margin 
\layout Standard

Quick way: Setting 
\begin_inset Formula \( \mu =\tan \theta  \)
\end_inset 

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \( F(\theta )=\frac{W\tan \theta }{\frac{\sin ^{2}\theta }{\cos \theta }+\cos \theta }=\frac{W\tan \theta \cos \theta }{(\sin ^{2}\theta +\cos ^{2}\theta )}=W\sin \theta  \)
\end_inset 


\end_float 
